27 March 1249":"před 27. března 1249","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, Anglie","Denton, Lancashire, England":"Denton, Lancashire, Anglie"},"da":{"1227–1272":"1227–1272","1227–1264":"1227–1264","1240–1293":"1240–1293","1260–1292":"1260–1292","1199–1249":"1199–1249","1215–1282":"1215–1282","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1227":"1227","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1227":"omkring 1227","1199":"1199","Bef 27 March 1249":"før 27. marts 1249","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Denton, Lancashire, England":"Denton, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"1227–1272":"1227–1272","1227–1264":"1227–1264","1240–1293":"1240–1293","1260–1292":"1260–1292","1199–1249":"1199–1249","1215–1282":"1215–1282","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1227":"1227","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1227":"circa 1227","1199":"1199","Bef 27 March 1249":"vóór 27 maart 1249","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Denton, Lancashire, England":"Denton, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1227–1272":"1227–1272","1227–1264":"1227–1264","1240–1293":"1240–1293","1260–1292":"1260–1292","1199–1249":"1199–1249","1215–1282":"1215–1282","1264":"1264","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","1227":"1227","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1227":"about 1227","1199":"1199","Bef 27 March 1249":"before 27 March 1249","Stockport, Cheshire, England":"Stockport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Denton, Lancashire, England":"Denton, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stockport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stopford","meanings":["English: locative name from Stockport (Cheshire), which is recorded as  <i>Stokeport</i> in 1188,  <i>Stockford</i> in 1283–8,  <i>Stopford</i> in 1347,  <i>Stoppord</i> in 1337, and  <i>Stapporte</i> in 1583."]}]},{"name":"Second","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French   Sicard  , reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. Compare   Secor   and   Sicord  .","History: The Secords are descendants of Ambroise Sicard, a Huguenot refugee from France (see   Sicard  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Sicard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Albertine, Aude, Benoit, Camille, Elzear, Francois, Jacques, Jean-Paul, Marcel, Monique, Numa.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sighard</i>, composed of the elements <i>sig</i> ‘victory’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. Compare   Seacord  ,   Secor  ,   Secord  ,   Secore  ,   Secoy  , and   Sicord  .","History: Jean Sicard from Mornac-sur-Seudre in Charente-Maritime, France, married Catherine Lauzon in Montreal, QC, in 1681. Jean-Baptiste Sicard, <i>sieur</i> de Carufel (see   Carufel  ), from Castres in Tarn, France, married Geneviève Raté in Saint-Pierre, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1694. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered forms <i>Sicord</i> and <i>Seacord</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. The Huguenot ancestor was Ambroise Sicard from France, who arrived with his wife and children in NY in the 1680s via England. His descendants (also) bear the surnames <i>Seacord</i>, <i>Secor</i>, <i>Secord</i>, and <i>Secoy</i>."]}]},{"name":"Baron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, English, Dutch, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and Croatian; Breton (also <b>Le Baron</b>): from Old French <i>barun</i>, <i>baron</i>, Middle English <i>barun</i>, <i>baroun</i>, Middle Dutch <i>baroen</i>, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and dialectal Croatian <i>baron</i> ‘baron’ (i.e. a nobleman ranking below an earl and above a knight), a title of nobility which was in England also awarded to certain freemen of the cities of London and York and of the Cinque Ports. As a surname it is unlikely to be a status name denoting a person of rank. Generally, it referred to service in a baronial household or was acquired as a nickname by a peasant who had ideas above his station or applied to a man showing characteristics of a nobleman. See also 3 and 4 below, compare   Barron   and   Lebaron  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Baron, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lebaron  .","German: status name for a freeman or baron, from <i>barūn</i> ‘imperial or church official’, a loanword in Middle High German from Old French (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Barron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Francisco, Carlos, Miguel, Raul, Pedro, Ruben, Alfredo, Luis.","Scottish: status name from Scots <i>baron</i>, which in the Highlands denoted a small proprietary landholder. In Angus it alluded specifically to a tenant of one of the small baronies attached to the Abbey of Coupar Angus. The surname was taken by Scottish migrants to Ulster. Compare   Baron  .","Scottish: shortened form of <b>McBarron</b>, from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bharain</b> ‘son of the baron’. See   Baron   and 1 above."]},{"name":"Boron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Krystyna, Edyta, Leszek, Mieczyslaw, Mieczyslawa, Wladyslaw.","Polish (<b>Boroń</b>): from a pet form of the personal names <i>Borzysław</i> or <i>Borzymir</i>, formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic <i>boriti se</i>).","French: habitational name from a place so called in Franche-Comté."]},{"name":"Baro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Manuel, Ana, Angel, Carlos, Cesar, Fernando, Jesus, Jose, Orlando, Ramon, Rosalia.  Italian Guido, Angelo, Carmelo, Federico, Lucio.","Catalan (<b>Baró</b>): status name from <i>baró</i> ‘free man, baron’ (see   Baron   1), or a habitational name from a place so named.","Hungarian (<b>Báró</b>): status name from <i>báró</i> ‘baron’. In the form <b>Baró</b>, it could be from a pet form of the personal names <i>Barabás</i> (see   Barabas  ) or <i>Bertalan</i>."]},{"name":"Barona","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of <b>Barón</b> ‘baron’ (see   Baron  ), applied as a nickname or as an occupational name for a member of the household of a baroness.","Italian: probably from the feminine form of   Barone  . The name is concentrated in Sondrio province (Lombardy)."]},{"name":"Barren","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Baron   or   Barran  ."]}]},{"name":"Stockport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Stopford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stopford","meanings":["English: locative name from Stockport (Cheshire), which is recorded as  <i>Stokeport</i> in 1188,  <i>Stockford</i> in 1283–8,  <i>Stopford</i> in 1347,  <i>Stoppord</i> in 1337, and  <i>Stapporte</i> in 1583."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"III","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Japanese Yuko, Aiko, Hideaki, Hiroki, Hiroyuki, Isamu, Kaoru, Katsumi, Keiichiro, Kenji, Masako, Masayuki.","Japanese: variously written, sometimes with characters used phonetically; the most probable meanings are 仁井 ‘benevolent well’, 新居 ‘new residence’, or 新井 ‘new well’. It is n